Myth: Long before the turning of ages, the world was shaped by two celestial architects: Ignis, who forged rivers of liquid gold, and Umbra, who sculpted mountains of bitter frost. For centuries, they shared the heavens in balance, but Umbra grew resentful of the mortals who gathered happily around Ignis’s warming fires, shunning the cold shadows.

Seeking absolute dominion, Umbra unleashed a suffocating gale, sealing the vibrant earth beneath a thick crust of black ice and freezing the great oceans. Heartbroken to see the mortals shivering and hopeless, Ignis ascended the highest summit. He struck his cosmic anvil, forging a radiant sun-sphere to melt his brother’s frozen grip. 

Enraged by this defiance, Umbra hurled a spear of absolute shadow, shattering the sun-sphere into thousands of glowing splinters. He laughed as the radiant shards rained down toward the frozen seas, believing the light was forever extinguished. 

But the collision of pure dawn and absolute frost sparked a resilient magic. As the shards struck the icy waters, they did not sink into darkness. Instead, the shattered embers surged upward, transforming into sweeping ribbons of ethereal light. These became the Northern Lights, a brilliant promise to mortals that warmth will always dance above the darkest winters.
